Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
push_ptn_network(25.10)                                push_ptn_network(25.10)

Name
       push_ptn_network  -  Pushes  down  a  network  (std cells and connected
       wires) logically and physically into overlapping partitions

Syntax
       push_ptn_network

       [-help]

       [-exclude_ptn_list <ptnNameList>]

       [-filter string]

       [-inst_prefix <instPrefixName>]

       [-logical_only]

       [-net_prefix <netPrefixName>]

       [-output_logical_only_nets string]

       [-output_nets_for_wire_distribution <string>]

       [-ptn_net_dir <fileName>]

       {-nets netNameList | -file  <fileName>  |  -buf_only  |  -insts  <inst-
       NameList> }

       [-check_only [-output<fileName>]]

       Pushes  down  a  network  (std cells and connected wires) logically and
       physically into overlapping partitions. The push_ptn_network command:

              *
                 Logically pushes down a set of nets into  overlapping  parti-
                tions by doing all the necessary logical port creations.

              *
                 Physically  pushes  down  the  special wires of the nets into
                overlapping partitions and does all  the  necessary  partition
                pin  creations.  The pushed wires look exactly the same as the
                original wires.

              * Creates Verilog assign statements wherever required to  ensure
                that  the pushed logic is logically equivalent to the original
                logic.

       Notes:

              * The push_ptn_network command does  not  support  designs  with
                master  and  clone partitions. In such scenarios, only masters
                will be seen and the  overlapping  wires  and  logic  will  be
                pushed down into masters only.

              * The  push_ptn_network command takes care of new nets connected
                at top level nets automatically post committing partitions.

              * The push_ptn_network command supports partially  routed  nets.
                It  does  not  require the wires of a net to be DRC/LVS clean.
                Wires need not connect to the  instance-pin  of  a  driver  or
                loads.  Even  if  a  wire  is in the 5u radius of a source-in-
                stance-pin or a sink-instance-pin, the tool considers the  net
                for pushdown.

Parameters
       -buf_only
              Specifies  that only all buffers, and their connected nets, will
              be considered for pushed down.

              Data_type: bool, required

       -check_only
              Informs which nets are going to be pushed down.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -exclude_ptn_list <ptnNameList>
              Specifies that the instances/nets within  the  specified  parti-
              tion(s) will not be pushed down.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -file <fileName>
              Specifies  the  name  of  the file that contains the list of net
              names to be considered for push down.

              Note: The net names should be listed in the file using the  fol-
              lowing format:

              set list_of_net_names_to_push_down { \

              <net_name_1>\

              <net_name_2>\

              }

              Note:  list_of_net_names_to_push_down,  as mentioned above, is a
              reserved keyword. Do not modify it.

              Data_type: string, required

       -filter <string>
              Specifies that only instances/nets whose name matches this spec-
              ified regular expression will be pushed down.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each push_ptn_network parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command: man push_ptn_network

       -inst_prefix <instPrefixName>
              Specifies a custom prefix for instances that are pushed down.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -insts <instNameList>
              Specifies  that all instances, and their connected nets, will be
              considered for pushed down.

              Note: The push_ptn_network command accepts instances names  with
              backspace '\' in them.

              Data_type: string, required

       -logical_only
              Logically pushes down network into overlapping partitions.

              Data_type: bool, optional

       -net_prefix <netPrefixName>
              Specifies a custom prefix for nets that are pushed down.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -nets <netNameList>
              Specifies that list of net names, and their connected instances,
              will be considered for pushed down.

              Note: The push_ptn_network command accepts nets names with back-
              space '\' in them.

              Data_type: string, required

       -output <fileName>
              Specifies  a  file  name  in which net names, to be pushed down,
              will be mentioned. This parameter is used with -check_only.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -output_logical_only_nets <string>
              Specifies a file name in which net names are mentioned. This pa-
              rameter is used with -logical_only.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -output_nets_for_wire_distribution <string>
              Outputs the user-specified nets so that they can be  used  later
              during the partition command.

              Data_type: string, optional

       -ptn_net_dir <fileName>
              Specifies the directory that consists of the names of the pushed
              nets corresponding to each partition.

              Data_type: string, optional

Example
              * The  following  command  consider  nets n1, n2 and n3 for push
                down.

                push_ptn_network -nets {n1 n2 n3}

              * The following command generates  a  file,  push_down_nets.txt,
                containing  the  names of nets that would have been considered
                for push down.

                push_ptn_network -nets [dbGet  -e  top.nets.name]  -check_only
                -output push_down_nets.txt

              * The  following  command  generates a file, push_down_nets.txt,
                containing the names of nets (connected to the  specified  in-
                stances)that would be considered for push down.

                push_ptn_network  -insts [dbGet -e top.insts.name] -check_only
                -output push_down_nets.txt

              * The following command considers all buffers for push down.

                push_ptn_network -buf_only

              * The following command considers all  buffers  and  their  con-
                nected  nets  for push down which have their hierarchical name
                (TCL) regexp matching to KK.*.

                push_ptn_network -buf_only -filter KK.*

              * The following command considers all  buffers  and  their  con-
                nected  nets  for push down. The pushed down buffers will have
                their base names starting with II_

                push_ptn_network -buf_only -inst_prefix II

              * The following command considers all  buffers  and  their  con-
                nected  nets  for push down. The pushed down buffers will have
                their base names starting with II_, and the pushed  down  nets
                will  have their base names starting with NN_.push_ptn_network
                -buf_only -inst_prefix II -net_prefix NN

